---
title: 06 · classic codecs
---

Q: The UTF-8 byte templates and payload bits per length.
A: 1 byte `0xxxxxxx` (7 bits); 2 bytes `110xxxxx 10xxxxxx` (11); 3 bytes `1110xxxx` + two continuations (16); 4 bytes `11110xxx` + three continuations (21). Most significant bits land in the lead byte.

---

Q: The UTF-8 length thresholds.
A: 1 byte for cp < 0x80, 2 for cp < 0x800, 3 for cp < 0x10000, 4 up to 0x10FFFF — each length is required to cover only what the previous cannot, which is exactly the shortest-form rule.

---

Q: Encode U+20AC (€), worked.
A: `0010 0000 1010 1100` (16 bits) → 3 bytes, split 4|6|6 → `E2 82 AC`.

---

Q: UTF-8 boundary vectors: 0x7F, 0x80, 0x7FF, 0x800, 0xFFFF, 0x10000, 0x10FFFF.
A: `7F`; `C2 80`; `DF BF`; `E0 A0 80`; `EF BF BF`; `F0 90 80 80`; `F4 8F BF BF`.

---

Q: What is forbidden outright in UTF-8?
A: Surrogates U+D800–DFFF (UTF-16 pairing machinery, ill-formed here); lead bytes `C0`, `C1` (can only start overlong 2-byte forms); `F5`–`FF` (beyond U+10FFFF, or the 5/6-byte forms RFC 3629 amputated in 2003).

---

Q: The UTF-8 decoder check order per sequence.
A: Classify the lead (`< 0x80` ASCII; `(b & 0xC0) == 0x80` lone continuation → reject; `> 0xF7` reject); truncation — all continuation bytes present; each continuation satisfies `(c & 0xC0) == 0x80`; assemble `cp = (cp << 6) | (c & 0x3F)`; then value checks on the assembled cp — overlong (below the minimum for the length), surrogate, above 0x10FFFF.

---

Q: One-expression test for a UTF-8 continuation byte?
A: `(b & 0xC0) == 0x80`.

---

Q: Why is `C0 AF` illegal even though it fits the 2-byte template bit-wise?
A: It encodes `/` (U+002F) in two bytes — overlong. Overlongs are a CVE class (the IIS/Nimda traversal, 2001): any system that validates strings before decoding and consumes them after is bypassable. Structural fix: reject `cp < min_for_length`; never blocklist byte values.

---

Q: Named production UTF-8 decoders, and the ASCII fast path?
A: Hoehrmann's DFA (canonical branchless table version), simdutf (vectorized). SWAR fast path: load 8 bytes; if `(chunk & 0x8080808080808080) == 0`, copy the whole chunk.

---

Q: Base64 unit mapping, alphabet, and output length.
A: 3 bytes = 24 bits = 4 sextets. A–Z (0–25), a–z (26–51), 0–9 (52–61), `+` (62), `/` (63); urlsafe swaps `+ /` for `- _`. Output is always $4\lceil n/3 \rceil$ with padding.

---

Q: Base64-encode "Man", worked.
A: `4D 61 6E` → `010011 010110 000101 101110` → 19, 22, 5, 46 → `TWFu`.

---

Q: The base64 tail rules.
A: 1 leftover byte → 2 chars + `==` (the 4 dangling bits of the 2nd char are zero); 2 leftover → 3 chars + `=` (2 dangling bits zero). Encoded length $\equiv 1 \pmod 4$ is unconditionally invalid — a lone sextet cannot produce a byte.

---

Q: Base64 decode validation, in order.
A: Length mod 4 == 0; `=` legal only as the final one or two chars (`===` never); every char through a 256-entry reverse table (strict decoders reject whitespace, `base64.b64decode` silently discards it — know which you're writing); optionally canonicality of the dangling bits.

---

Q: Base64 malleability?
A: Non-zero dangling bits give one byte string several encodings — `TQ==` and `TR==` both decode to `M` if you ignore them. Anything deduping, caching, or verifying signatures over the encoded form must reject non-zero trailing bits or re-encode and compare.

---

Q: Recover padding for unpadded base64url (JWT/JWS)?
A: `s + "=" * (-len(s) % 4)`; remainder 2 → 1 byte, remainder 3 → 2 bytes.

---

Q: Manual hex encode, and decode validation?
A: Per byte: `HEX[b >> 4]` then `HEX[b & 0x0F]` over `'0123456789abcdef'`. Decode via reverse table (256 entries with a poison value in C, dict in Python); reject odd length and non-hex chars. `bytes.fromhex` skips ASCII spaces — replicate or don't, but say so out loud.

---

Q: RLE byte pairs: worst case, and when it pays?
A: `count value` pairs, count 1..255, maximal runs split greedily (300 × A → `FF 41 2D 41`). Round-trips arbitrary bytes; worst case 2x expansion (all runs length 1); pays off iff mean run length > 2.

---

Q: PackBits control-byte semantics, and why it beats naive pairs?
A: c in 0..127: copy next c+1 literal bytes; 129..255: repeat next byte 257−c times; 128: no-op. Worst-case overhead 1/128 instead of 2x — the standard answer to "your RLE doubles random data".

---

Q: Where does RLE actually win?
A: Wherever long runs meet a need for O(1) state and branch-trivial decode: bitmap indexes, sparse masks, Parquet definition/repetition levels (its RLE + bit-pack hybrid), quantized sensor streams, fax (ITU T.4), BWT output — the stage that makes bzip2 work.

---

Q: The delta → zigzag → uvarint stack: what each stage buys.
A: Delta: sorted-ish sequences have small gaps — store `x[i] - x[i-1]` (state your convention for the head). Zigzag: two's-complement $-1$ is FF…FF, a 10-byte uvarint, while zigzag($-1$) = 1 is one byte — small magnitudes stay small in both signs. Uvarint: 7 bits per byte, so small ints get small encodings. Lineage: protobuf sint64, Kafka v2 batches, Lucene posting gaps, Parquet DELTA_BINARY_PACKED, Gorilla → Prometheus.

---

Q: Encode [1000, 1005, 1004, 1010] through the delta stack.
A: Deltas 1000, 5, −1, 6 → zigzag 2000, 10, 1, 12 → `D0 0F 0A 01 0C` — 5 bytes against 32 as raw u64, 6.4:1.

---

Q: The delta-overflow problem and its resolution.
A: For int64 inputs $\max - \min$ can be $2^{64} - 1$, which does not fit int64. Real formats define deltas with wrapping mod-$2^{64}$ arithmetic (Parquet says so explicitly): C unsigned subtraction wraps free, Python masks with `& MASK64`, and the decoder recovers exact values because addition mod $2^{64}$ is a group. Do the arithmetic unsigned in C — signed overflow is UB.

---

Q: Bitpacking: what must you state before writing any code?
A: The bit order. LSB-first (Parquet's RLE/bit-packed hybrid): value $i$ owns stream bits $ik$ to $(i+1)k - 1$; stream bit $j$ lives at bit $j \bmod 8$ of byte $\lfloor j/8 \rfloor$; unused final bits are zero. Parquet's deprecated BIT_PACKED level encoding is MSB-first — both orders coexist inside one format, and mixing them corrupts silently.

---

Q: The bitpacking encoder accumulator idiom.
A: `acc |= v << nbits; nbits += k`, then while `nbits >= 8`: emit `acc & 0xFF`, `acc >>= 8`, `nbits -= 8`.

---

Q: Bitpack [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] at k = 3.
A: 15 bits → 2 bytes: `D1 58`.

---

Q: The two instant bitpack sanity checks.
A: k = 8 must be the identity on bytes; k = 1 of `[1,0,1,1,0,0,1,0]` must be `4D`. They catch bit-order bugs before anything else does.

---

Q: The checksum ladder, weakest to strongest.
A: Additive sum: catches every single-byte change, blind to reordering (commutative) and balanced ±deltas. Bare XOR: strictly weaker — byte pairs XORed with the same mask cancel, and a duplicated block vanishes entirely. Fletcher-16: position-weighted, detects reordering, still two adds per byte, no tables. CRC-32: polynomial division over $GF(2)$, detects all bursts up to register width. Adversarial setting: none of these — keyed MAC.

---

Q: Fletcher-16: the update rule and the position-weighting argument.
A: `s1 = (s1 + b) % 255; s2 = (s2 + s1) % 255`; result `(s2 << 8) | s1`. Since $s_2 = \sum_i (n - i + 1)\, b_i \bmod 255$, bytes are weighted by position, so reordering is detected. Adler-32 is the same design mod 65521 with s1 starting at 1.

---

C: Fletcher-16 reduces mod [255], so a byte flipped between 0x00 and 0xFF is invisible.

---

Q: Why modulus 255 rather than 256 in Fletcher?
A: The sums can then be computed with one's-complement carry folds (the RFC 1071 Internet-checksum trick). The cost is the $\texttt{0x00} \equiv \texttt{0xFF}$ blind spot.

---

Q: Fletcher-16 of "abcde"?
A: `0xC8F0` (s1 = 240, s2 = 200).

---

Q: The checksum field placement idiom?
A: Compute over header + payload with the checksum field zeroed; the verifier recomputes with the field zeroed and compares. (Or define the check over payload only — the verifier mirrors the choice.)

---

Q: Gorilla XOR float compression, in three sentences.
A: XOR each f64 with its predecessor: unchanged value → a single 0 bit; changed → `10` + reuse the previous leading/trailing-zero window, or `11` + 5 bits of leading-zero count + 6 bits of window length + the significant bits. Timestamps get delta-of-delta bucketed into size classes. About 1.37 bytes per 16-byte point on production telemetry ($\approx$ 12:1); Prometheus TSDB and InfluxDB TSM are direct descendants — the same accumulator machinery with a predictor bolted on.

---

Q: Java "modified UTF-8", WTF-8, utf8mb3 — one line each.
A: Java: U+0000 as `C0 80` (so C strings never contain NUL) plus 6-byte surrogate pairs, in JNI and class files — strict decoders reject both. WTF-8: deliberately admits unpaired surrogates so arbitrary Windows UTF-16 (filenames) round-trips; Rust's `OsStr`. utf8mb3: MySQL's legacy 3-byte cap — 4-byte codepoints (emoji) explode old schemas; always test 0xFFFF/0x10000 across any boundary.

---

Q: The Unicode-recommended error policy for invalid UTF-8?
A: Substitute one U+FFFD per maximal subpart, then resync at the next plausible lead byte. The alternative policy is raising — state which you implement.

---

Q: `(-7) % 255` in Python vs C, and the codec consequence?
A: 248 vs $-7$ — keep C checksum accumulators unsigned.

---

Q: How many codepoints does the 3-byte UTF-8 form legitimately cover?
A: `0x10000 - 0x800 - 2048 = 61440` (the surrogates are carved out).

---

Q: Bytes to bitpack 100 five-bit values?
A: $\lceil 500/8 \rceil = 63$.

---

Q: zigzag($-3$), and the general map?
A: 5; negatives go to odds ($2|n| - 1$), non-negatives to evens ($2n$).
